At Nottingham Trent University, our BSc (Hons) Computing and IT programmes have been accredited by the British Computer Society (BCS), which means they meet the standards set by the industry for producing graduates with the right skills and knowledge.

The key objectives of BCS's IT education programme in preparing students for careers in digital and technology occupations include:

* Developing a strong foundation in programming principles, data structures, algorithms, computer systems, and software engineering;
* Building practical skills in areas such as web development, mobile app development, data analysis, and cybersecurity;
* Cultivating problem-solving, critical thinking, and collaboration skills through group projects and assignments;
* Preparing students for professional certifications, such as those offered by BCS, to demonstrate their expertise and commitment to the profession;
* Fostering a deep understanding of the social, ethical, and environmental implications of technology and its applications;
* Providing opportunities for students to engage with industry partners, attend guest lectures, and participate in hackathons and coding challenges to stay up-to-date with the latest trends and technologies.

